This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\n/*\n    requires div != 0;\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures *out == (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. That is, no for, while, do-while or recursive loops\n\nYou are given the following problem description. At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that there exists at least one magic square that meets the conditions.\n*/\n/*@ predicate ExistsSolution(integer b, integer c, integer d, integer f, integer g, integer h) =\n    \\exists integer a, e, i;\n    0 <= a <= 100000 && 0 <= e <= 100000 && 0 <= i <= 100000 &&\n    a + b + c == a + d + g && a + b + c == b + e + h && a + b + c == c + f + i &&\n    a + b + c == a + e + i && a + b + c == c + e + g && a + b + c == d + e + f &&\n    a + b + c == d + e + f && a + b + c == g + h + i;\n\n*/\n/*@ predicate IsValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer d, integer 100000 &&\n    0 <= g <= 100000 && 0 <= h <= 100000 && 0 <= i <= 100000 &&\n    0 <= sum && sum == a + b + c && sum == d + e + f && sum == g + h + i &&\n    sum == a + d + g && sum == b + e + h && sum == c + f + i &&\n    sum == a + e + i && sum == c + e + g;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out_a) && \\valid(out_b) && \\valid(out_c);\n    requires \\valid(out_d) && \\valid(out_e) && ensures IsValidSolution(*out_a, *out_b, *out_c, *out_d, *out_e, *out_f, *out_g, *out_h, *out_i);\n*/\nvoid restoreMagicSquare(int a, int b, int c, int d, int e, int f, int g, int h, int i, int *out_a, int *out_b, int *out_c, int *out_d, int *out_e, int *out_f, int *out_g, int *out_h, int *out_i);\n```\n\nPlease generate the formally verified C code adhering to the problem description.",

Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square.                     "code": "/*\n    Little Elephant loves magic squares very much. A magic square is a 3 \u00d7 3 table, each cell contains some positive integer. At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that there exists at least one magic square that meets the conditions.\n*/\n/*@ predicate ExistsSolution(integer b, integer c, integer d, integer f, integer g, integer h) =\n    \\exists integer a, e, i;\n    0 <= a <= 100000 && 0 <= e <= 100000 && 0 <= i <= 100000 &&\n    a + b + c == a + d + g && a + b + c == b + e + h && a + b + c == c + f + i &&\n    a + b + c == a + e + i && a + b + c == c + e + g && a + b + c == d + e + f &&\n    a + b + c == d + e + f && a + b + c == g + h + i;\n\n*/\n/*@ predicate IsValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer d, integer e, integer f, integer g, integer h, integer i) =\n    \\exists integer sum;\n    0 <= a <= 100000 && 0 <= b <= 100000 && 0 <= c <= 100000 &&\n    0 <= d <= 100000 && 0 <= e <= 100000 && 0 <= f <= 100000 &&\n    0 <= g <= 100000 && 0 <= h <= 100000 && 0 <= i <= 100000 &&\n    0 <= sum && sum == a + b + c && sum == d + e + f && sum == g + h + i &&\n    sum == a + d + g && sum == b + e + h && sum == c + f + i &&\n    sum == a + e + i && sum == c + e + g;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out_a) && \\valid(out_b) && \\valid(out_c);\n    requires \\valid(out_d) && \\valid(out_e) && \\valid(out_f);\n    requires \\valid(out_g) && \\valid(out_h) && \\valid(out_i);\n    requires \\separated(out_a, out_b, out_c, out_d, out_e, out_f, out_g, out_h, out_i);\n    requires a == 0 && e == 0 && i == 0;\n    requires 1 <= b <= 100000 && 1 <= c <= 100000 && 1 <= d <= 100000;\n    requires 1 <= f <= 100000 && 1 <= g <= 100000 && 1 <= h <= 100000;\n    requires ExistsSolution(b, c, d, f, g, h);\n    assigns *out_a, *out_b, *out_c, *out_d, *out_e, *out_f, *out_g, *out_h, *out_i;\n    ensures *out_b == b && *out_c == c && *out_d == d && *out_f == f && *out_g == g && *out_h == h;\n    ensures IsValidSolution(*out_a, *out_b, *out_c, *out_d, *out_e, *out_f, *out_g, *out_h, *out_i);\n*/\nvoid restoreMagicSquare(int a, int b, int c, int d, int e, int f, int g, int h, int i, int *out_a, int *out_b, int *out_c, int *out_d, int *out_e, int *out_f, int *out_g, int *out_h, int *out_i) {\n    *out_a = b + c - d;\n    *out_e = b + c - g;\n    *out_i = b + c - f;\n\n    *out_b = b;\n    *out_c = c;\n    *out_d = d;\n    *out_f = f;\n    *out_g = g;\n    *out_h = h;\n\n    *out_i = i;\n}\n",

Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\n/*\n    requires div != 0;\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures *out == (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. That is, no for, while, do-while or recursive loops\n\nYou are given the following problem description. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Little Elephant loves magic squares very much. A magic square is a 3 \u00d7 3 table, each cell contains some positive integer. At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that there exists at least one magic square that meets the conditions.\n*/\n/*@ predicate ExistsSolution(integer b, integer c, integer d, integer f, integer g, integer h) =\n e, integer f, integer g, integer h, integer i) =\n    \\exists integer sum;\n    0 <= a <= 100000 && 0 <= b <= 100000 && 0 <= c <= 100000 &&\n    0 <= d <= 100000 && 0 <= e <= 100000 && 0 <= f <= This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. == c + f + i &&\n    sum == a + e + i && sum == c + e + g;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out_a) && \\valid(out_b) && \\valid(out_c);\n    requires \\valid(out_d) && \\valid(out_e) && int *out_b, int *out_c, int *out_d, int *out_e, int *out_f, int *out_g, int *out_h, int *out_i);\n```\n\nPlease generate the formally verified C code adhering to the problem description.",

At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Little Elephant loves magic squares very much. A magic square is a 3 \u00d7 3 table, each cell contains some positive integer. At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that there exists at least one magic square that meets the conditions.\n*/\n/*@ predicate ExistsSolution(integer b, integer c, integer d, integer f, integer g, integer h) =\n Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\n/*\n    requires div != 0;\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures *out == (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. That is, no for, while, do-while or recursive loops\n\nYou are given the following problem description. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Little Elephant loves magic squares very much. A magic square is a 3 \u00d7 3 table, each cell contains some positive integer. At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\n/*\n    requires div != 0;\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures *out == (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. That is, no for, while, do-while or recursive loops\n\nYou are given the following problem description. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Little Elephant loves magic squares very much. A magic square is a 3 \u00d7 3 table, each cell contains some positive integer. At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that there exists at least one magic square that meets the conditions.\n*/\n/*@ predicate ExistsSolution(integer b, integer c, integer d, integer f, integer g, integer h) =\n i && a + b + c == c + e + g && a + b + c == d + e + f &&\n    a + b + c == d + e + f && a + b + c == g + h + i;\n\n*/\n/*@ predicate IsValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer d, integer == c + f + i &&\n    sum == a + e + i && sum == c + e + g;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out_a) && \\valid(out_b) && \\valid(out_c);\n    requires \\valid(out_d) && \\valid(out_e) && int *out_b, int *out_c, int *out_d, int *out_e, int *out_f, int *out_g, int *out_h, int *out_i);\n```\n\nPlease generate the formally verified C code adhering to the problem description.",

The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Little Elephant loves magic squares very much. A magic square is a 3 \u00d7 3 table, each cell contains some positive integer. At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that there exists at least one magic square that meets the conditions.\n*/\n/*@ predicate ExistsSolution(integer b, integer c, integer d, integer f, integer g, integer h) =\n Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\n/*\n    requires div != 0;\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures *out == (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. That is, no for, while, do-while or recursive loops\n\nYou are given the following problem description. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Little Elephant loves magic squares very much. A magic square is a 3 \u00d7 3 table, each cell contains some positive integer. At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that there exists at least one magic square that meets the conditions.\n*/\n/*@ predicate ExistsSolution(integer b, integer c, integer d, integer f, integer g, integer h) =\n i && a + b + c == c + e + g && a + b + c == d + e + f &&\n    a + b + c == d + e + f && a + b + c == g + h + i;\n\n*/\n/*@ predicate IsValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer d, integer == c + f + i &&\n    sum == a + e + i && sum == c + e + g;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out_a) && \\valid(out_b) && \\valid(out_c);\n    requires \\valid(out_d) && \\valid(out_e) && \\valid(out_f);\n    requires \\valid(out_g) && \\valid(out_h) && \\valid(out_i);\n    requires \\separated(out_a, out_b, out_c, out_d, out_e, out_f, out_g, out_h, out_i);\n    requires a == 0 && e == int *out_b, int *out_c, int *out_d, int *out_e, int *out_f, int *out_g, int *out_h, int *out_i);\n```\n\nPlease generate the formally verified C code adhering to the problem description.",

Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\n/*\n    requires div != 0;\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures *out == (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . == c + f + i &&\n    sum == a + e + i && sum == c + e + g;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out_a) && \\valid(out_b) && \\valid(out_c);\n    requires \\valid(out_d) && \\valid(out_e) && Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that there exists at least one magic square that meets the conditions.\n*/\n/*@ predicate ExistsSolution(integer b, integer c, integer d, integer f, integer g, integer h) =\n Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\n/*\n    requires div != 0;\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures *out == (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. That is, no for, while, do-while or recursive loops\n\nYou are given the following problem description. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Little Elephant loves magic squares very much. A magic square is a 3 \u00d7 3 table, each cell contains some positive integer. At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that there exists at least one magic square that meets the conditions.\n*/\n/*@ predicate ExistsSolution(integer b, integer c, integer d, integer f, integer g, integer h) =\n This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. == c + f + i &&\n    sum == a + e + i && sum == c + e + g;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out_a) && \\valid(out_b) && \\valid(out_c);\n    requires \\valid(out_d) && \\valid(out_e) &&                     "tokens_used": 0,
                    "code": "/*\n    Little Elephant loves magic squares very much. A magic square is a 3 \u00d7 3 table, each cell contains some positive integer. At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. That is, no for, while, do-while or recursive loops\n\nYou are given the following problem description. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Little Elephant loves magic squares very much. A magic square is a 3 \u00d7 3 table, each cell contains some positive integer. At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that there exists at least one magic square that meets the conditions.\n*/\n/*@ predicate ExistsSolution(integer b, integer c, integer d, integer f, integer g, integer h) =\n == c + f + i &&\n    sum == a + e + i && sum == c + e + g;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out_a) && \\valid(out_b) && \\valid(out_c);\n    requires \\valid(out_d) && \\valid(out_e) && Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\n/*\n    requires div != 0;\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures *out == (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. That is, no for, while, do-while or recursive loops\n\nYou are given the following problem description. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Little Elephant loves magic squares very much. A magic square is a 3 \u00d7 3 table, each cell contains some positive integer. At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that there exists at least one magic square that meets the conditions.\n*/\n/*@ predicate ExistsSolution(integer b, integer c, integer d, integer f, integer g, integer h) =\n    \\exists integer a, e, i;\n    0 <= a <= 100000 && 0 <= e <= 100000 && 0 <= i <= 100000 &&\n    a + b + c == a + d + g && a + b + c == b + e + h && a + b + c == c + f + i &&\n    a + b + c == a + e + i && a + b + c == c + e + g && a + b + c == d + e + f &&\n    a + b + c == d + e + f && a + b + c == g + h + i;\n\n*/\n/*@ predicate IsValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer d, integer e, integer f, integer g, integer h, integer i) =\n    \\exists integer sum;\n    0 <= a <= 100000 && 0 <= b <= 100000 && 0 <= c <= 100000 &&\n    0 <= d <= 100000 && 0 <= e <= 100000 && 0 <= f <= 100000 &&\n    0 <= g <= 100000 && 0 <= h <= 100000 && 0 <= i <= 100000 &&\n    0 <= sum && sum == a + b + c && sum == d + e + f && sum == g + h + i &&\n    sum == a + d + g && sum == b + e + h && sum == c + f + i &&\n    sum == a + e + i && sum == c + e + g;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out_a) && \\valid(out_b) && \\valid(out_c);\n    requires \\valid(out_d) && \\valid(out_e) && \\valid(out_f);\n    requires \\valid(out_g) && \\valid(out_h) && \\valid(out_i);\n    requires \\separated(out_a, out_b, out_c, out_d, out_e, out_f, out_g, out_h, out_i);\n    requires a == 0 && e == 0 && i == 0;\n    requires 1 <= b <= 100000 && 1 <= c <= 100000 && 1 <= d <= 100000;\n    requires 1 <= f <= 100000 && 1 <= g <= 100000 && 1 <= h <= 100000;\n    requires ExistsSolution(b, c, d, f, g, h);\n    assigns *out_a, *out_b, *out_c, *out_d, *out_e, *out_f, *out_g, *out_h, *out_i;\n    ensures *out_b == b && *out_c == c && *out_d == d && *out_f == f && *out_g == g && *out_h == h;\n    ensures IsValidSolution(*out_a, *out_b, *out_c, *out_d, *out_e, *out_f, *out_g, *out_h, *out_i);\n*/\nvoid restoreMagicSquare(int a, int b, int c, int d, int e, int f, int g, int h, int i, int *out_a, Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. == c + f + i &&\n    sum == a + e + i && sum == c + e + g;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out_a) && \\valid(out_b) && \\valid(out_c);\n    requires \\valid(out_d) && \\valid(out_e) && The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . That is, no for, while, do-while or recursive loops\n\nYou are given the following problem description. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Little Elephant loves magic squares very much. A magic square is a 3 \u00d7 3 table, each cell contains some positive integer. At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that there exists at least one magic square that meets the conditions.\n*/\n/*@ predicate ExistsSolution(integer b, integer c, integer d, integer f, integer g, integer h) =\n Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that there exists at least one magic square that meets the conditions.\n*/\n/*@ predicate ExistsSolution(integer b, integer c, integer d, integer f, integer g, integer h) =\n    \\exists integer a, e, i;\n    0 <= a <= 100000 && 0 <= e <= 100000 && 0 <= i <= 100000 &&\n    a + b + c == a + d + g && a + b + c == b + e + h && a + b + c == c + f + i &&\n    a + b + c == a + e + i && a + b + c == c + e + g && a + b + c == d + e + f &&\n    a + b + c == d + e + f && a + b + c == g + h + i;\n\n*/\n/*@ predicate IsValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer d, integer e, integer f, integer g, integer h, integer i) =\n    \\exists integer sum;\n    0 <= a <= 100000 && 0 <= b <= 100000 && 0 <= c <= 100000 &&\n    0 <= d <= 100000 && 0 <= e <= 100000 && 0 <= f <= 100000 &&\n    0 <= g <= 100000 && 0 <= h <= 100000 && 0 <= i <= 100000 &&\n    0 <= sum && sum == a + b + c && sum == d + e + f && sum == g + h + i &&\n    sum == a + d + g && sum == b + e + h && sum == c + f + i &&\n    sum == a + e + i && sum == c + e + g;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out_a) && \\valid(out_b) && \\valid(out_c);\n    requires \\valid(out_d) && \\valid(out_e) && \\valid(out_f);\n    requires \\valid(out_g) && \\valid(out_h) && \\valid(out_i);\n    requires \\separated(out_a, out_b, out_c, out_d, out_e, out_f, out_g, out_h, out_i);\n    requires a == 0 && e == 0 && i == 0;\n    requires 1 <= b <= 100000 && 1 <= c <= 100000 && 1 <= d <= 100000;\n    requires 1 <= f <= 100000 && 1 <= g <= 100000 && 1 <= h <= 100000;\n    requires ExistsSolution(b, c, d, f, g, h);\n    assigns *out_a, *out_b, *out_c, *out_d, *out_e, *out_f, *out_g, *out_h, *out_i;\n    ensures *out_b == b && *out_c == c && *out_d == d && *out_f == f && *out_g == g && *out_h == h;\n    ensures IsValidSolution(*out_a, *out_b, *out_c, *out_d, *out_e, *out_f, *out_g, *out_h, *out_i);\n*/\nvoid restoreMagicSquare(int a, int b, int c, int d, int e, int f, int g, int h, int i, int *out_a, int *out_b, int *out_c, int *out_d, int *out_e, int *out_f, int *out_g, int *out_h, int *out_i);\n```\n\nPlease generate the formally verified C code adhering to the problem description.",

Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . \\valid(out_f);\n    requires \\valid(out_g) && \\valid(out_h) && \\valid(out_i);\n    requires \\separated(out_a, out_b, out_c, out_d, out_e, out_f, out_g, out_h, out_i);\n    requires a == 0 && e == Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\n/*\n    requires div != 0;\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures *out == (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. That is, no for, while, do-while or recursive loops\n\nYou are given the following problem description. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Little Elephant loves magic squares very much. A magic square is a 3 \u00d7 3 table, each cell contains some positive integer. At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . i && a + b + c == c + e + g && a + b + c == d + e + f &&\n    a + b + c == d + e + f && a + b + c == g + h + i;\n\n*/\n/*@ predicate IsValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer d, integer == c + f + i &&\n    sum == a + e + i && sum == c + e + g;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out_a) && \\valid(out_b) && \\valid(out_c);\n    requires \\valid(out_d) && \\valid(out_e) && ensures IsValidSolution(*out_a, *out_b, *out_c, *out_d, *out_e, *out_f, *out_g, *out_h, *out_i);\n*/\nvoid restoreMagicSquare(int a, int b, int c, int d, int e, int f, int g, int h, int i, int *out_a, int *out_b, int *out_c, int *out_d, int *out_e, int *out_f, int *out_g, int *out_h, int *out_i);\n```\n\nPlease generate the formally verified C code adhering to the problem description.",

It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\n/*\n    requires div != 0;\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures *out == (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that there exists at least one magic square that meets the conditions.\n*/\n/*@ predicate ExistsSolution(integer b, integer c, integer d, integer f, integer g, integer h) =\n i && a + b + c == c + e + g && a + b + c == d + e + f &&\n    a + b + c == d + e + f && a + b + c == g + h + i;\n\n*/\n/*@ predicate IsValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer d, integer == c + f + i &&\n    sum == a + e + i && sum == c + e + g;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out_a) && \\valid(out_b) && \\valid(out_c);\n    requires \\valid(out_d) && \\valid(out_e) && Additionally it checks if a given integer x is a multiple of another integer div.  If either condition is not satisfied, the function returns false. This operation ensures that x adheres to specific numeric constraints related to both value and divisibility.\n\n    input:\n        The function takes four integers x, low, high and div. x is the number to be checked, and low and high are the lower and upper bounds of the range, respectively. The function also takes an integer div which is the number to be checked for divisibility.\n\n    output:\n        One output will be given which returns true if both conditions are met, i.e., if x is within the range [low, high] and simultaneously a multiple of div.\n*/\n/*\n    requires div != 0;\n    requires \\valid(out);\n    assigns *out;\n    ensures *out == (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n*/\nvoid checkConstraints(int x, int low, int high, int div, int *out)\n{\n    *out = (x >= low && x <= high && x % div == 0);\n}\n```\n\nYou must adhere to the following rules:\n * Do not add an explanation to the code\n * Only give the output function, do not repeat the specification\n * Do not make use of any type of loops. That is, no for, while, do-while or recursive loops\n\nYou are given the following problem description. You must return the code in the following format:\n```C\n/*\n    Little Elephant loves magic squares very much. A magic square is a 3 \u00d7 3 table, each cell contains some positive integer. At that the sums of integers in all rows, columns and diagonals of the table are equal. The figure below shows the magic square, the sum of integers in all its rows, columns and diagonals equals 15. The Little Elephant remembered one magic square. He started writing this square on a piece of paper, but as he wrote, he forgot all three elements of the main diagonal of the magic square. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 . Help the Little Elephant, restore the original magic square, given the Elephant's notes.\n\n    Input\n    The first three lines of the input contain the Little Elephant's notes. The first line contains elements of the first row of the magic square. The second line contains the elements of the second row, the third line is for the third row. The main diagonal elements that have been forgotten by the Elephant are represented by zeroes. It is guaranteed that the notes contain exactly three zeroes and they are all located on the main diagonal. It is guaranteed that all positive numbers in the table do not exceed 10^5.\n\n    Output\n    Output nine values representing the grid \u2014 the Little Elephant's magic square. If there are multiple magic squares, you are allowed to print any of them.\n\n    Note\n    that all numbers you print must be positive and not exceed 10^5 . It is guaranteed that there exists at least one magic square that meets the conditions.\n*/\n/*@ predicate ExistsSolution(integer b, integer c, integer d, integer f, integer g, integer h) =\n i && a + b + c == c + e + g && a + b + c == d + e + f &&\n    a + b + c == d + e + f && a + b + c == g + h + i;\n\n*/\n/*@ predicate IsValidSolution(integer a, integer b, integer c, integer d, integer == c + f + i &&\n    sum == a + e + i && sum == c + e + g;\n*/\n\n/*@\n    requires \\valid(out_a) && \\valid(out_b) && \\valid(out_c);\n    requires \\valid(out_d) && \\valid(out_e) && \\valid(out_f);\n    requires \\valid(out_g) && \\valid(out_h) && \\valid(out_i);\n    requires \\separated(out_a, out_b, out_c, out_d, out_e, out_f, out_g, out_h, out_i);\n    requires a == 0 && e == ensures IsValidSolution(*out_a, *out_b, *out_c, *out_d, *out_e, *out_f, *out_g, *out_h, *out_i);\n*/\nvoid restoreMagicSquare(int a, int b, int c, int d, int e, int f, int g, int h, int i, int *out_a, int *out_b, int *out_c, int *out_d, int *out_e, int *out_f, int *out_g, int *out_h, int *out_i);\n```\n\nPlease generate the formally verified C code adhering to the problem description.",

                    "code": "/*\n    Little Elephant loves magic squares very much. A magic square is a 3 \u00d7 3 table, each cell contains some positive integer. Fortunately, the Little Elephant clearly remembered that all elements of the magic square did not exceed 10^5 .
